* Exploring Orb-mode

** Tables

|  n |  n^2 |     cos(n) |   log(n)   |
|----+------+------------+------------|
|  1 |    1 | 0.99984770 |          0 |
|  2 |    4 | 0.99939083 | 0.69314718 |
| 33 | 1089 | 0.83867057 |  3.4965076 |
| 44 | 1936 | 0.71933980 |  3.7841896 |
| .1 | 0.01 | 0.99999848 | -2.3025851 |
#+TBLFM: $2=$1^2::$3=cos($1)::$4=log($1)

** Code blocks

This code blocks can be triggered by TAB-expanding the ~<s~ string

#+begin_src python
import numpy as np

print(np.random.uniform(-1, 1, 10))
#+end_src

#+RESULTS:
: None

#+begin_src emacs-lisp
(message "Hello LOOO ooo")
#+end_src

#+RESULTS:
: Hello LOOO ooo

#+begin_src C
int main() {
printf("%s", "Hello");
return 0;
}
#+end_src

#+RESULTS:
: Hello

#+begin_src gnuplot :export={code, results} :file graph.png
f(x) = x**2
plot f(x)
#+end_src

#+RESULTS:

** Latex stuff

Latex is rendered putting the cursor on the source and issuing ~C-c C-x C-l~

$i \hbar \frac{\partial}{\partial t}\Psi(\mathbf{r},t) = \hat H \Psi(\mathbf{r},t)$

** HTML export

   Simply execute the ~org-html-export-to-html~ command in the minibuffer. 


